"2ESSENTIAL THEOLOGY | VOD Slide Build Out\nSession Number Session Topics Completed?\n1 Introduction to Essential Theology Yes\n2 The Trinity Yes\n3 Attributes of God Yes\n4 Bibliology Yes\n5 Humanity + Sin Yes\n6 Jesus, Part 1 Yes\n7 Jesus, Part 2 Yes\n8 Salvation, Part 1 Yes\n9 Salvation, Part 2 Yes\n10 Sanctification Yes\n11 The Church Yes\n12 Eschatology Yes\nSession Breakdown //\nJosh\n\u25cf Trinity\n\u25cf Jesus Pt 2\n\u25cf The Church\n\u25cf Eschatology\nEmma\n\u25cf Intro to ET\n\u25cf Bibliology\n\u25cf Humanity + Sin\n\u25cf Sanctification\nJake\n\u25cf Attributes of God\n\u25cf Salvation Pt 1\n\u25cf Salvation Pt 2\n\u25cf Jesus Pt 1\n1\nSession 1: Introduction to Essential Theology\nTeacher: Grant Partrick\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology1 (0:10)\nSlide 1: Goal for the Course (0:44)\nOur goal for creating this course is to introduce you to a theological framework and give\nyou a tool belt that will equip you for a lifetime pursuit of following Jesus.\nSlide 2: James 4:8 (1:07)\n\u201cDraw near to God and He will draw near to you.\u201d\nSlide 3: God\u2019s Plan (1:33)\nGod has a plan for your life, and it is for you to grow and mature in your faith, trust, and\nrelationship with Him\nSlide 4: 2 Peter. 1:3-8 (1:50)\n\u201cHis divine power has given us everything we need for a godly life through our\nknowledge of him who called us by his own glory and goodness. Through these he has\ngiven us his very great and precious promises, so that through them you may\nparticipate in the divine nature, having escaped the corruption in the world caused by\nevil desires.\u201d\nSlide 5: 2 Peter. 1:5-8 (1:57)\n\u201cFor this very reason, make every effort to add to your faith goodness; and to goodness,\nknowledge; and to knowledge, self-control; and to self-control, perseverance; and to\nperseverance, godliness; and to godliness, mutual affection; and to mutual affection,\nlove. For if you possess these qualities in increasing measure, they will keep you from\nbeing ineffective and unproductive in your knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ.\u201d\n1 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n2\nSlide 6: What Is Theology? (5:09)\nTheology is the study of God: His nature, His character, who He is, and what He is like\nSlide 7: What Is Theology? (5:52)\n\u201cYou have made us for yourself, O Lord, and our hearts are restless until they rest in\nYou.\u201d - Saint Augustine\nSlide 8: What Is Theology? (6:19)\n1. You were created by God\n2. You were created for God\nSlide 9: John 7:28 (7:28)\n\u201cNow this is eternal life: that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom\nyou have sent.\u201d\nSlide 10: Matthew 22:37 (7:50)\n\u201cJesus replied: \u201cLove the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and\nwith all your mind.\u201d\nSlide 11: What Is Theology? (8:32)\n\u201cWhat comes into our minds when we think about God is the most important thing about\nus\u201d - A.W. Tozer\nSlide 12: What Is Theology? (8:54)\nRight Thinking -> Right Believing -> Right Living\nSlide 13: What Is Theology? (9:16)\n\u201cWhat we think about will determine what we care about. And what we care about, we\nwill chase\u201d - Ben Stuart\n3\nSlide 14: What Is Theology? (10:36)\n\u201cTheology is important because life is hard.\u201d\nSlide 15: Three Theological Anchors (11:29)\n1. The Glory of God\n2. Radical Grace\n3. Extravagant Worhsip\nSlide 16: What Is Theology? (13:00)\nOrthos = straight\nDoxa = belief or thinking\nOrthodoxy = right thinking\nSlide 17: Seven Areas of Orthodox Christian Theology (13:39)\n1. The Trinity and the Characteristics of God\n2. Inerrancy of Scripture\n3. Humanity and Sin\n4. Jesus Christ\n5. Salvation\n6. Sanctification and The Church\n7. Eschatology\nSlide 18: What Is Theology? (14:31)\nChiseled in stone = Dogma; Unchanging\nSlide 19: What Is Theology? (14:47)\nChiseled in stone = Dogma; Unchanging\nCarved in wood = Doctrines; Largely and consistently believed in the Church\nSlide 20: What Is Theology? (15:06)\nChiseled in stone = Dogma; Unchanging\nCarved in wood = Doctrines; Largely and consistently believed in the Church\nWritten on paper = Less firm than doctrines\n4\nSlide 21: What Is Theology? (15:22)\nChiseled in stone = Dogma; Unchanging\nCarved in wood = Doctrines; Largely and consistently believed in the Church\nWritten on paper = Less firm than doctrines\nDrawn in the sand = debatable topics (i.e. eschatology)\nStatic Graphic (15:54)\nSlide 22: Philippians 1:9-11 (18:32)\n\u201cAnd this is my prayer: that your love may abound more and more in knowledge and\ndepth of insight, so that you may be able to discern what is best and may be pure and\nblameless for the day of Christ, filled with the fruit of righteousness that comes through\nJesus Christ\u2014to the glory and praise of God.\u201d\n5\nSession 2: The Trinity (Josh)\nTeacher: Grant Partrick\nSlide 1: Static Graphic\nSlide 2: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God | Bibliology |\nHumanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation, Part 2 |\nSanctification | The Church | Eschatology (00:00)\nSlide 3: The Trinity (00:15)\nWho Is God?\nSlide 4: Who Is God? (00:23)\n\"What comes into our minds when we think about God is the most important thing about\nus.\u201d - A.W. Tozer\nSlide 5: Who Is God? (01:00)\n\u201cTheology is taught by God, teaches of God, and leads to God.\u201d - Thomas Aquinas\nSlide 6: Who Is God? (02:23)\nIt\u2019s possible to know a lot about God and to not know God.\nSlide 7: Who Is God? (02:48)\nThe goal of this section is not to gain more information about Him but that we would\nknow who He is.\nSlide 8: Who Is God? (03:08)\n\u201cTo know and grow to enjoy God is what we are saved for\u2026 Thus, (to study the trinity) is\nnot to play an intellectual game. In fact, we will see that the triune nature of God affects\neverything from how we listen to music to how we pray: it makes for happier marriages,\nwarmer dealings with others, better church life; it gives Christian assurance, shapes\nholiness and transforms the very way we look at the world around us. No exaggeration:\nthe knowledge of this God turns lives around.\u201d -Michael Reeves, Delighting in The\n6\nTrinity\nSlide 9: Who Is God? (04:06)\n\u201cWhat makes Christianity absolutely distincy is the identity of our God. Which God we\nworship: that is the article of faith that stands before all others. The bedrock of faith is\nnothing less than God himself, and every aspect of the gospel - creation, revelation,\nsalvation - is only Christian insofar as it is the creation, revelation, and salvation of this\nGod, the triune God.\u201d -Michael Reeves, Delighting in The Trinity\nSlide 10: Who Is God? (04:40)\nOur God is Triune: God the Father, God the Son, and God the Holy Spirit.\nSlide 11: Who Is God? (07:15)\nThree Central Truths:\n1. Our God is One God.\n2. Our God is Three Persons\n3. Each Person is fully God.\nSlide 12: Who Is God? (07:55)\nOur God is:\n1. Equal in attributes\n2. Diverse in roles and relationship\n3. Singularly unified as one God.\nSlide 13: Our God is One. (08:18)\n\u25cf \u201cHear, O Israel: The LORD our God, the LORD is one\u201d (Deut. 6:4).\n\u25cf We are \u2018Monotheists\u2019\nSlide 14: Our God is One. (09:09)\n\u201cIn the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God. He\nwas with God in the beginning. Through him all things were made; without him nothing\nwas made that has been made. In him was life, and that life was the light of all mankind.\nThe light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it\u201d (John 1:1-5).\n7\nSlide 15: Our God is One. (12:33)\nThe Doctrine of the Trintiy: Our God is One God and our God is Three Persons: Father,\nSon, and Holy Spirit.\nSlide 16: Our God is Three Persons (12:45)\n\u201cThe Bible also indicates that the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are distinct Persons. For\nexample, since the Father sent the Son into the world (John 3:16), He cannot be the\nsame person as the Son. Likewise, after the Son returned to the Father (John 16:10),\nthe Father and the Son sent the Holy Spirit into the world (John 14:26; Acts 2:33). The\nFather is not the Son, the Son is not the Holy Spirit, and the Holy Spirit is not the\nFather.\u201d - Ben Stuart\nSlide 17: Our God is Three Persons (13:51)\nExamples of The Trinity in Scripture:\n- Creation\n- The Baptism of Jesus\n- The promise of the Spirit in Acts 1\nSlide 18: Our God is Three Persons (15:00)\nModalism/Sabellianism - The doctrine that the persons of the Trinity represent only\nthree \u201cmodes\u201d or aspects of the divine revelation, not distinct and coexisting persons in\nthe divine nature.\nSlide 19: Each Person is Fully God (15:44)\nEach Person of the Trinity is completely and fully God\nSlide 20: Who Is God? (16:23)\nThree Central Truths:\n1. Our God is One God.\n2. Our God is Three Persons.\n3. Each Person is fully God.\nSlide 21: Who Is God? (16:45)\n8\nOur God is:\n1. Equal in attributes\n2. Diverse in roles and relationship\n3. Singularly unified as one God.\nSlide 22: Equal in Attributes (16:54)\n\u25cf Each Person is fully God.\n\u25cf Each Person is deserving of glory.\nSlide 23: Diverse in Roles and Relationship (17:14)\n\u201cSo it is, the Bible tells us. Each of the Divine persons centers upon the other. None\ndemands that the others revolve around Him. Each voluntarily circles the other two,\npouring love, delight, and adoration into them. Each person of the Trinity loves, adores,\ndefers to, and rejoices in the others. The early leaders of the Greek church had a word\nfor this: perichoresis. Notice our word \u201cchoreography\u201d within it.\u201d - Tim Keller, Reason for\nGod\nSlide 24: Diverse in Roles and Relationship (17:46)\n\u2018Perichoresis\u2019 - The Greek word referring to the relationship between the Persons of the\nTrinity\nSlide 25: Singularly unified as one God (18:00)\n\u201cTherefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the\nFather and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, and teaching them to obey everything I have\ncommanded you. And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age\u201d (Matt.\n28:18-20).\nSlide 26: Three Words to Keep in Mind (18:26)\n\u25cf Equality - Equal in attributes.\n\u25cf Diversity - Diverse in roles and relationship.\n\u25cf Unity - Singularly unified as one God.\nSlide 27: Equality, Diversity & Unity (18:34)\n9\nCHART **Figure out how to cite the chart **Consider asking about animation for this\nchart.**2\nSlide 28: Roles + Relationships (21:20)\n\u201cHe said to them: \u201cIt is not for you to know the times or dates the Father has set by his\nown authority. But you will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes on you; and you\nwill be my witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the\nearth\u201d\u201d (Acts 1:7-8).\nSlide 29: God the Father - Divine Source of Creation (22:16)\n\u201cFor God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in him, and through him to reconcile\nto himself all things, whether things on earth or things in heaven, by making peace\nthrough his blood, shed on the cross\u201d (Col. 1:19-20).\nSlide 30: God the Son - Vehicle of Creation (23:17)\n\u201cThe Son is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn over all creation. For in him all\nthings were created: things in heaven and on earth, visible and invisible, whether thrones\nor powers or rulers or authorities; all things have been created through him and for him.\nHe is before all things, and in him all things hold together\u201d (Col. 1:15-17).\nSlide 31: God the Spirit - The Life-Giver to Creation (24:10)\n\u201cNow the earth was formless and empty, darkness was over the surface of the deep,\nand the Spirit of God was hovering over the waters\u201d (Gen. 1:2).\nSlide 32: God the Spirit - The Life-Giver to Creation (24:29)\n\u201cBy the word of the LORD the heavens were made, their starry host by the breath of his\nmouth\u201d (Ps. 33:6).\n2 We want to re-design this chart and add animation (if possible) to help contribute to Grant\u2019s explanation.\n10\nSlide 33: God the Spirit - The Life-Giver to Creation (24:40)\n\u201cThe Spirit of God has made me; the breath of the Almighty gives me life\u201d (Job 33:4).\nSlide 34: Application (25:24)\nWe pray to the Father.\nWe pray by the Spirit.\nWe pray through the Son.\nSlide 35: Three Central Truths (25:38)\n1. Our God is One God.\n2. Our God is Three Persons.\n3. Each Person is fully God.\n11\nSession 3: Attributes of God - V4 (Jake)\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology3\nSlide 1: Recap of the Trinity (00:40)\n\u25cf Our God is one God.\n\u25cf Our God is three persons.\n\u25cf Each person is fully God.\nSlide 2: Recap of the Trinity Continued (1:00)\nOf these three persons, they are\n\u25cf Distinct in roles and relationships.\n\u25cf Equal in glory and characteristics\n\u25cf Singularly unified as one God.\nSlide 3: What comes to your mind when you think about the attributes of God? (4:35)\nSlide 4: Attributes of God (4:50)\nHe is a God who is\u2026\nEternal, Full of Faithfulness, Foreknowing, Good, Holy\nImmutable, Impartial, Incomprehensible, Infinite, Jealous, A God of Justice,\nLongsuffering, Patience, Love, Mercy\nSlide 5: Attributes of God, continued (5:07)\nOmnipotent,Omnipresent, Omniscient\nRighteous, Self-existent, Self-sufficient, Sovereign, Transcendent, Truth, Wise,\nRighteously Wrathful, Full of Splendor, and Full of Strength\n3 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n12\nSlide 6: Just because God is inexhaustible doesn\u2019t mean that he\u2019s not worth pursuing\n(6:15)\nSlide 7: God\u2019s Different Types of Attributes (7:57)\nIncommunicable Attributes = attributes that humans cannot relate to\nExamples\n\u25cf God is Eternal (Ps. 90)\n\u25cf God is Immutable (Heb. 13:8)\n\u25cf God is Holy (Isa. 6, Rev. 4- 5)\nSlide 8: God\u2019s Different Types of Attributes (9:00)\nCommunicable Attributes = attributes humans can see and witness; attributes humans\ncan practice\nExamples\n\u25cf God is good (Ps. 100:5).\n\u25cf Out of His goodness flows love, mercy, grace, justice, kindness,\ncompassion, and patience. (Ex. 34:5-8, Eph. 2, Rom. 2:4)\nSlide 9: Why is it important to know what God is like? (11:15)\nLearning about who God is helps convince our souls to love God more.\nSlide 10: How does knowing what God is like help your theology? (11:40)\nIt helps:\n\u25cf Widen our perspective of how He rules.\nSlide 11: How does knowing what God is like help your theology? (12:08)\nIt helps:\n\u25cf Widen our perspective of how He rules.\n\u25cf Deepen our appreciation of who He is.\nSlide 12: How does knowing what God is like help your theology? (12:55)\n13\nIt helps:\n\u25cf Widen our perspective of how He rules.\n\u25cf Deepen our appreciation of who He is.\n\u25cf Heighten our awe of what He has done.\nSlide 13: How does knowing what God is like help your theology? (14:10)\nIt helps:\n\u25cf Widen our perspective of how He rules.\n\u25cf Deepen our appreciation of who He is.\n\u25cf Heighten our awe of what He has done.\n\u25cf Who He is helps clarify who we are.\nSlide 14: Isaiah 55:8-9 (15:18)\n\u201cFor my thoughts are not your thoughts,\nneither are your ways my ways, declares the Lord.\nFor as the heavens are higher than the earth,\nso are my ways higher than your ways\nand my thoughts than your thoughts.\u201d\nSlide 15: We want to worship a big God (16:01)\nGod is at all times pursuing the elevation and maximization of the perfection of his\nholiness.\nSlide 16: Romans 11:33-36 (17:03)\n\u201cOh, the depth of the riches and wisdom and knowledge of God! How unsearchable are\nhis judgments and how inscrutable his ways!\u201d\nSlide 17: Romans 11:33-36 (17:24)\n\u201cFor who has known the mind of the Lord,\nor who has been his counselor?\u201d\n\u201cOr who has given a gift to him\nthat he might be repaid?\u201d\nFor from him and through him and to him are all things. To him be glory forever. Amen.\n14\nSlide 18: God is Eternal (19:16)\n\u25cf God is completely outside of time.\n\u25cf Time based words like before, later, then, now - don\u2019t apply to God.\n\u25cf There has never been something new that He has to adjust to.\nSlide 19: God is Eternal (20:15)\n\u201cLord, you have been our dwelling place in all generations. Before the mountains were\nbrought forth, or ever you had formed the earth and the world, from everlasting to\neverlasting you are God. You return man to dust and say, \u201cReturn, O children of man!\u201d\nFor a thousand years in your sight are but as yesterday when it is past, or as a watch in\nthe night\u201d (Ps. 90:1-4).\nSlide 20: God is Immutable (20:31)\n\u201cJesus Christ is the same yesterday, and today, and forever\u201d (Heb. 13:8).\n\u201cFor I the Lord do not change, therefore you, oh children of Jacob, are not consumed\u201d\n(Mal. 3:6).\nSlide 21: God is Immutable (21:13)\n\u25cf He is self-satisfying.\n\u25cf There has never been a moment where he\u2019s been lacking\n\u25cf There\u2019s never been a moment where he\u2019s been without\nSlide 22: God is Holy (21:34)\n\u25cf He is set apart.\n\u25cf Everything about Him and His goodness is different from us.\n\u25cf It is the essence of who God is.\nSlide 23: God is Holy (22:52)\n\u201cOf all the attributes of God, holiness is the one that most uniquely describes Him and in\nreality is the summation of all His other attributes. The word holiness refers to His\nseparateness, His otherness, the fact that He is unlike any other being. It indicates His\ncomplete and infinite perfection. Holiness is the attribute of God that binds all the others\ntogether.\u201d John MacArther\n15\nSlide 24: God is Omniscient, Omnipotent, and Omnipresent (23:26)\n\u25cf God is all-knowing\n\u25cf God is all-powerful\n\u25cf God is all places\nSlide 25: God is Omniscient, Omnipotent, and Omnipresent (23:37)\n\u201cI make known the end from the beginning, from ancient times, what is still to come. I\nsay, 'My purpose will stand, and I will do all that I please\u201d (Isa. 46:10).\nSlide 26: God is Omniscient, Omnipotent, and Omnipresent (24:28)\n\u201cOnce God has spoken; twice have I heard this; that power belongs to God, and that to\nyou, O Lord, belongs steadfast love\u201d (Ps. 61:11-12)\nSlide 27: God is Omniscient, Omnipotent, and Omnipresent (25:21)\n\u201cScience observes how the power of God operates, discovers a regular pattern\nsomewhere and fixes it as a \u201claw.\u201d The uniformity of God\u2019s activities in His creation\nenables the scientist to predict the course of natural phenomena. The trust-worthiness\nof God\u2019s behavior in His world is the foundation of all scientific truth.\u201d - A.W. Tozer\nSlide 28: God is Omniscient, Omnipotent, and Omnipresent (26:15)\n\u201cI am with you and will watch over you wherever you go, and I will bring you back to this\nland. I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised you\" (Gen. 28:15).\nSlide 29: God is Relatable (27:44)\n\u201cO Lord, our Lord, how majestic is your name in all the earth! You have set your glory\nabove the heavens\u2026. When I look at your heavens, the work of your fingers, the moon\nand the stars, which you have set in place, what is man that you are mindful of him, and\nthe son of man that you care for him?\u201d (Ps. 8:1, 3-4).\nSlide 30: God is Faithful (28:00)\n16\n\u201cGod is true. His Word of Promise is sure. In all His relations with His people, God is\nfaithful. He may be safely relied upon. No one ever yet really trusted Him in vain.\u201d - A.W.\nPink\n\u201cHe who calls you is faithful; he will surely do it\u201d (1 Thess. 5:24).\nSlide 31: God is Good (28:38)\n\u201cFor the Lord is good; his steadfast love endures forever, and his faithfulness to all\ngenerations\u201d (Ps. 100:5).\nSlide 32: God is Good (28:49)\nOut of His goodness flows love, mercy, grace, justice, kindness, compassion, and\npatience (Ex. 34:5-8, Eph. 2, Rom. 2:4)\nSlide 33: God is Good (28:59)\n\u201cSince God\u2019s first concern for His universe is holiness, whatever is contrary to this is\nnecessarily under His eternal displeasure. To preserve His creation God must destroy\nwhatever would destroy it.\u201d A.W. Tozer\nSlide 34: God is the Just and the Justifier (31:05)\n\u201cHe did it to demonstrate his righteousness at the present time, so as to be just and the\none who justifies those who have faith in Jesus\u201d (Rom. 3:26).\nSlide 35: Final Takeaways (31:33)\n1. All of His attributes work together.\n2. He is both Majestic and glorious, yet desires to be in relationship with us.\nSlide 36: To Fear and Not Be Afraid (31:50)\n\u201cThe greatness of God rouses fear within us, but his goodness encourages us to not be\nafraid of Him. To fear and not be afraid, that is the paradox of faith\u201d AW Tozer\n17\nSession 4: Bibliology (Emma)\nTeacher: Aaron Coe\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 |\nSalvation, Part 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology4\nSlide 1: Two Key Components of Bibliology (0:30)\n1. What is the Bible?\n2. Why is the Bible reliable? Why can we trust it?\nSlide 2: What is the Bible? (2:40)\nThe Bible is the primary way that God has revealed Himself to the world.\nSlide 4: What is the Bible? (2:54)\n\u201cAll Scripture is breathed out by God and profitable for teaching, for reproof, for\ncorrection, and for training in righteousness, that the man of God may be complete,\nequipped for every good work\u201d (2 Tim 3:16).\nSlide 5: What is the Bible? (3:46)\n1. God reveals Himself through His Word\nSlide 6: Hebrews 4:12 (3:52)\n\u201cFor the word of God is alive and active. Sharper than any double-edged sword, it\npenetrates even to dividing soul and spirit, joints and marrow; it judges the thoughts and\nattitudes of the heart.\u201d\nSlide 7: What is the Bible? (4:12)\n1. God reveals Himself through His Word.\n2. God reveals Himself through the person of Jesus Christ and the Holy Spirit.\n4 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n18\nSlide 8: Hebrews 1:1-3 (4:20)\n\u201cLong ago, at many times and in many ways, God spoke to our fathers by the prophets,\nbut in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son, whom he appointed the heir of all\nthings, through whom also he created the world. He is the radiance of the glory of God\nand the exact imprint of his nature, and he upholds the universe by the word of his\npower.\u201d\nSlide 9: What is the Bible? (5:01)\n1. God reveals Himself through His Word.\n2. God reveals Himself through the person of Jesus Christ and the Holy Spirit.\n3. God reveals Himself through His creation\nSlide 10: Psalm 19:1-2 (5:07)\n\u201cA psalm of David. The heavens declare the glory of God; the skies proclaim the work of\nHis hands. Day after day they pour forth speech; night after night they reveal\nknowledge.\u201d\nSlide 11: Romans 1:19-20 (5:20)\n\u201cFor what can be known about God is plain to them, because God has shown it to them.\nFor his invisible attributes, namely, his eternal power and divine nature, have been\nclearly perceived, ever since the creation of the world, in the things that have been\nmade.\u201d\nSlide 12: Thoughts from 2 Timothy 3:16 (6:50)\n1. Scripture is breathed out by God.\n2. Scripture is profitable.\n3. Scripture does not return empty.\n4. Scripture:\na. teaches us.\nb. reproves us.\nc. corrects us.\nd. trains us.\nSlide 13: What is the Bible? (8:19)\n\u201cAll Scripture is God-breathed\u2026\u201d (2 Tim. 3:16)\n19\nGreek Word: Theo-pneustos\n\u25cf Theo = God\n\u25cf Pneustos = power, force, wind\nSlide 14: What does it mean that Scripture is God-breathed? (8:42)\n1. The Scripture is God\u2019s words, not man\u2019s words.\nSlide 15: What does it mean that Scripture is God-breathed? (9:17)\n1. The Scripture is God\u2019s words, not man\u2019s words.\n2. The Scripture is useful, and it changes something in our lives.\nSlide 16: What is Scripture? (9:40)\n\u25cf Scripture is a collection of unique books written by man, divinely inspired by God\n\u25cb 66 books total (39 Old Testament, 27 New Testament).\n\u25cb A collection of different genres.\n\u25cb Written in 3 languages: Hebrew, Aramaic, and Greek.\nSlide 17: What is Scripture? (10:18)\n\u25cf Scripture is a collection of unique books written by man, divinely inspired by God\n\u25cb 66 books total (39 Old Testament, 27 New Testament).\n\u25cb A collection of different genres.\n\u25cb Written in 3 languages: Hebrew, Aramaic, and Greek.\n\u25cf Scripture\u2019s purpose is to reveal the character and nature of God.\n\u25cf Scripture illuminates truth and is life giving.\nSlide 18: What is Scripture? (10:30)\n\u25cf Scripture is a collection of unique books written by man, divinely inspired by God\n\u25cb 66 books total (39 Old Testament, 27 New Testament).\n\u25cb A collection of different genres.\n\u25cb Written in 3 languages: Hebrew, Aramaic, and Greek.\n\u25cf Scripture\u2019s purpose is to reveal the character and nature of God.\n\u25cf Scripture illuminates truth and is life giving.\n\u25cf Scripture is infallible (incapable of making mistakes or being wrong).\n20\nSlide 19: Infallibility of Scripture (11:12)\n\u201cThe sum of your word is truth, and every one of your righteous rules endures forever\u201d\n(Ps 119:160).\nSlide 20: Infallibility of Scripture (12:02)\n\u201c By no means! Let God be true though every one were a liar, as it is written, \u201cThat you\nmay be justified in your words, and prevail when you are judged\u201d (Rom 3:4).\nSlide 21: Infallibility of Scripture (12:20)\n\u201cSanctify them by the truth; your word is truth\u201d (John 17:17).\nSlide 22: What is Scripture? (12:31)\n\u25cf Scripture\u2019s purpose is to reveal the character and nature of God.\n\u25cf Scripture illuminates truth and is life giving.\n\u25cf Scripture is infallible (incapable of making mistakes or being wrong).\n\u25cf Scripture is the complete work of God.\nSlide 23: What is Scripture? (13:02)\n\u25cf Scripture\u2019s purpose is to reveal the character and nature of God.\n\u25cf Scripture illuminates truth and is life giving.\n\u25cf Scripture is infallible (incapable of making mistakes or being wrong).\n\u25cf Scripture is the complete work of God.\n\u25cf Scripture is historically verifiable.\nSlide 24: What is Scripture? (14:20)\n\u201cThe author is always doing something with what the author is saying,\u201d - Dr. Mark\nYarbrough\nSlide 25: Summary Points on \u201cWhat is the Bible?\u201d (15:05)\n1. The Scripture expresses all things necessary for God\u2019s glory.\n2. It is entirely true and reliable.\n3. It is the final authority.\n21\nSlide 26: Why is the Scripture Reliable?(15:35)\nSlide 27: Three Points for the Bible\u2019s Reliability (16:30)\n1. Manuscript Evidence\n2. Historical Accuracy of the Writing\n3. Internal Proofs\nSlide 28: Manuscript Evidence (17:10)\nThe Bible is the most reliable piece of historical literature in existence.\nSlide 29: Reliability in Historical Literature (17:34)\n1. There are multiple eyewitnesses that viewed the Scripture being made and\nwritten\nSlide 30: Reliability in Historical Literature (17:58)\n1. There are multiple eyewitnesses that viewed the Scripture being made and\nwritten.\n2. Ancient literature was recorded in manuscripts. The amount of manuscripts\navailable determined the veracity of that text.\nSlide 31: Manuscript Evidence (18:25)\n\u25cf Caesar\u2019s Gallic War = 10 copies\nSlide 32: Manuscript Evidence (18:35)\n\u25cf Caesar\u2019s Gallic War = 10 copies\n\u25cf New Testament (24,000 + total)\n\u25cb In Greek = 5,000+ copies\n\u25cb In Latin = 10,000+ copies\n\u25cb Other languages = 9,000+ copies\nSlide 33: Three Points for the Bible\u2019s Reliability (22:52)\n1. Manuscript Evidence.\n2. Historical Accuracy of the Writing.\n22\n3. Internal Proofs.\nSlide 34: Historical Accurcy of Writing (32:00)\nThe Scriptures are first and foremost a history book.\nSlide 35: Three key points as to why we can be sure that the Bible is reliable (25:30)\n1. Manuscript Evidence\n2. Historical Accuracy of the Writing\n3. Internal Proofs\nSlide 36: Internal Proofs (25:47)\n1. New Testament eyewitness to debunk the New Testament if it was wrong.\nSlide 37: Internal Proofs (27:09)\n1. New Testament eyewitness to debunk the New Testament if it was wrong.\n2. Seeming contradictions that lend to its trustworthiness.\nSlide 38: Internal Proofs (29:32)\n1. New Testament eyewitness to debunk the New Testament if it was wrong\n2. Seeming contradictions that lend to its trustworthiness.\n3. Accuracy of Old Testament Prophecies.\nSlide 39: Examples of Old Testament Prophecy Fulfillment (29:58)\n\u25cf Messiah born in Bethlehem [Micah 5:2 -> Matthew 2:1-6]\n\u25cf John the Baptist would prepare the way [Malachi 3:1 -> Mark 1:1-3]\n\u25cf Jesus would ride on a donkey [Zechariah 9:9 -> John 12:12-15]\n\u25cf Jesus would be sold for 30 pieces of silver, and the money would be used to buy\na potter\u2019s field. [Zechariah 11:13 -> Matthew 27:3-10]\n\u25cf Jesus would make no defense during his trial [Isaiah 53:7 -> Mark 14:61]\n\u25cf Jesus would be crucified and his robe would be divided [Psalm 22:16-18 ->\nMatthew 27:35]\nSlide 40: Internal Proofs (32:00)\n23\n1. New Testament eyewitness to debunk the New Testament if it was wrong.\n2. Seeming contradictions that lend to its trustworthiness.\n3. Accuracy of Old Testament Prophecies.\n4. Criterion of Embarrassment.\nSlide 41: Static Graphic (33:40)\n24\nSession 5: Humanity + Sin (Emma)\nTeacher: Brad Jones\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 |\nSalvation, Part 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology5\nSlide 1: Humanity + Sin (00:47)\nWe are seeking to understand:\n1. Our value\n2. Our problem\nSlide 2: Humanity + Sin (1:25)\nYour understanding of humanity and sin are instrumental in how you perceive\n\u25cf the work of Christ,\n\u25cf the act of salvation,\n\u25cf the process of sanctification,\n\u25cf the necessity of the church,\n\u25cf the reality of eternity and future glory.\nSlide 3: What is humanity? (2:15)\n\u25cf We are created in the image of God, unique, purposed, and made to worship and\nreflect God\u2019s glory in the world.\nSlide 4: What is humanity? (2:35)\n\u25cf We are created in the image of God, unique, purposed, and made to worship and\nreflect God\u2019s glory in the world.\n\u25cf We have been given a God-given mandate on the earth to be fruitful and multiply\nand subdue the earth. It\u2019s a stewardship over all creation.\nSlide 5: Humanity (3:04)\n5 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n25\n\u201cThe chief end of man is to glorify God and enjoy him forever.\u201d - Westminster\nCatechesim\nSlide 6: Humanity (3:39)\n\u201cGod is most glorified when we are most satisfied in Him.\u201d - Pastor John Piper\nSlide 7: Imago Dei (5:21)\nThe Scripture tells us that we are made in the Image of God (the Imago Dei).\nSlide 8: Genesis 1:27 (5:43)\n\u201cSo God created mankind in his own image,\nin the image of God he created them;\nmale and female he created them.\u201d\nSlide 9: The Imago Dei (6:47)\nWhat does it mean that we are made in the image of God?\n1. It gives all humanity dignity\nSlide 10: The Imago Dei (7:42)\nWhat does it mean that we are made in the image of God?\n1. It gives all humanity dignity.\n2. All people, every race, people group, both genders, all ages, regardless of\ndisability have value and dignity.\nSlide 11: The Scriptures on the Imago Dei (8:12)\n\u25cf \"Whoever sheds man's blood, By man his blood shall be shed, For in the image\nof God He made man.\u201d (Gen 9:6)\n\u25cf \u201cWith it we bless our Lord and Father, and with it we curse people who are made\nin the likeness of God. From the same mouth come blessing and cursing. My\nbrothers, these things ought not to be so.\u201d (Jas 3:9-10)\nSlide 12: The Imago Dei (8:59)\n26\n\u201cMade In His Image\u201d is a profound announcement. This is the thing God immediately\ndeclares upon creating Adam and Eve. Adam and Eve are not just part of the catalog of\ncreatures that God made. They are above, they're special, and they are christened with\na dignity that separates them from everything else. We must never ever forget this\nfoundational definition of who human beings are. With these words, God names the\nintrinsic worth of people. This worth is never earned and cannot be taken away. To be\nhuman is to have dignity and worth because you carry the image of God himself.\u201d - Paul\nDavid Tripp\nSlide 13: The \u201cImage of God\u201d (10:04)\nBeing \u201cmade in the image of God\u201d gives you:\n\u25cf identity,\n\u25cf meaning,\n\u25cf purpose,\n\u25cf how we are meant to function,\n\u25cf destiny.\nSlide 14: Imago Dei (10:42)\n\u201cGod saw all that he had made, and it was very good\u2026\u201d (Gen 1:31).\nSlide 15: Made in the Image of God (12:26)\n4 primary handles to understand \u201cmade in the image of God:\u201d\n1. Relationship\nSlide 16: John 17:20-21 (12:40)\n\u201cI do not ask for these only, but also for those who will believe in me through their word,\nthat they may all be one, just as you, Father, are in me, and I in you, that they also may\nbe in us, so that the world may believe that you have sent me.\u201d\nSlide 17: Made in the Image of God (13:30)\n4 primary handles to understand \u201cmade in the image of God:\u201d\n1. Relationship.\n2. Morality.\nSlide 18: Made in the Image of God (14:15)\n27\n4 primary handles to understand \u201cmade in the image of God:\u201d\n1. Relationship.\n2. Morality.\n3. Spirituality.\nSlide 19: Made in the Image of God (15:40)\nFour Anchors of \u201cImago Dei:\u201d\n1. Relationship.\n2. Morality.\n3. Spirituality.\n4. Representation.\nSlide 20: Humanity + Sin (17:05)\nTitle only\nSlide 21: Humanity + Sin (17:44)\n\u25cf Though made righteous, humanity chose to rebel against God, and they fell from\nglory.\n\u25cf Disbelief led to disobedience which led to separation from God, which ultimately\nleads at the end of time, to eternal death.\n\u25cf Sin is both inherited (original sin) and chosen (personal choice).\nSlide 22: Sin (18:47)\n\u201cSin is making good things ultimate things.\u201d - Tim Keller\nSlide 23: Genesis 6:5 (19:29)\n\u201cThe Lord saw how great the wickedness of the human race had become on the earth,\nand that every inclination of the thoughts of the human heart was only evil all the time.\u201d\nSlide 24: Ephesians 2:1-3 (22:04)\n\u201cAs for you, you were dead in your transgressions and sins, in which you used to live\nwhen you followed the ways of this world and of the ruler of the kingdom of the air, the\nspirit who is now at work in those who are disobedient. All of us also lived among them\n28\nat one time, gratifying the cravings of our flesh and following its desires and thoughts.\nLike the rest, we were by nature deserving of wrath.\u201d\nSlide 25: Romans 3:21-24 (23:29)\n\u201cBut now apart from the law the righteousness of God has been made known, to which\nthe Law and the Prophets testify. This righteousness is given through faith in Jesus\nChrist to all who believe. There is no difference between Jew and Gentile, for all have\nsinned and fall short of the glory of God, and all are justified freely by his grace through\nthe redemption that came by Christ Jesus.\u201d\nSlide 26: The Scope of Sin (24:22)\nPastor John Piper says that sin is:\n\u25cf The glory of God not honored.\n\u25cf The holiness of God not reverenced.\n\u25cf The greatness of God not admired.\n\u25cf The power of God not praised.\n\u25cf The truth of God not sought.\n\u25cf The wisdom of God not esteemed.\n\u25cf The beauty of God not treasured.\n\u25cf The goodness of God not savored.\n\u25cf The faithfulness of God not trusted.\n\u25cf The promises of God not believed.\n\u25cf The commandments of God not obeyed.\n\u25cf The justice of God not respected.\n\u25cf The wrath of God not feared.\n\u25cf The grace of God not cherished.\n\u25cf The presence of God not prized.\n\u25cf The person of God not loved.\nSlide 27: Our Definition of Sin (25:08)\nSinning is any feeling or thought or speech or action that comes from a heart that does\nnot treasure God over all other things.\nSin is the complete corruption of every faculty and part of our soul and body.\nSlide 28: Sin in Our Daily Lives (25:50)\n29\n1. Sin is a matter of the heart.\nSlide 29: Sin in Our Daily Lives (26:22)\n1. Sin is a matter of the heart.\n2. Sin blinds us.\nSlide 30: Sin in Our Daily Lives (26:35)\n1. Sin is a matter of the heart.\n2. Sin blinds us.\n3. Sin complicates things.\nSlide 31: Sin in Our Daily Lives (26:52)\n1. Sin is a matter of the heart.\n2. Sin blinds us.\n3. Sin complicates things.\n4. Sin brings about the war of life.\nSlide 32: Sin in Our Daily Lives (27:00)\n1. Sin is a matter of the heart.\n2. Sin blinds us.\n3. Sin complicates things.\n4. Sin brings about the war of life.\n5. Without the theology of sin, there is no basis for the chaos of the world.\nSlide 33: Static Slide (27:10)\nSlide 34: Isaiah 53:5-6 (29:05)\n\u201cBut he was pierced for our transgressions; he was crushed for our iniquities; upon him\nwas the chastisement that brought us peace, and with his wounds we are healed. All we\nlike sheep have gone astray; we have turned\u2014every one\u2014to his own way; and the Lord\nhas laid on him the iniquity of us all.\u201d\n30\nSession 6: Jesus Pt 1 - V4 (Jake)\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology6\nSlide 1: What Comes to Your Mind When You Think About Jesus? (00:46)\nSlide 2: Jesus and Christian Theology (3:16)\n\u201cThe Christian religion stands or falls with the person of Jesus Christ\u2026at the center of\nany Christian theology, therefore, must stand the person of Christ; Who did Jesus of\nNazareth claim to be?\u201d William Lane Craig\nSlide 3: Who is Jesus? (4:05)\n\u201cWho is Jesus? We can\u2019t escape him. We\u2019ve tried to run from him but there he is. He\nkeeps popping up everywhere. Our greatest philosophers write about him. Our greatest\nhistorians write about him. Our greatest poems and plays are about him. Our greatest\narchitecture is about him.\u201d All of us are sinners, but Jesus was tempted in every point\nlike we were... He was a man. Just like you. But he was more than that. He claimed to\nbe the unique, only begotten, incarnate son of God. In fact, he claimed pre-existence\u2026\nNo wonder they got angry. No wonder they threw stones at him. No wonder they tired to\nkill him and no wonder they eventually did crucify him. He stood and said, \u201cI am God.\u201d\nBilly Graham\nSlide 4: The Apostles Creed (5:51)\n6 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n31\n\u201cI believe in God the Father Almighty, Maker of heaven and earth, and in Jesus Christ,\nhis only begotten Son, our Lord. He was conceived by the Holy Ghost, and born of the\nvirgin, Mary. He suffered under Pontius Pilate, was crucified, died, and was buried. He\ndescended into Hades. On the third day He rose again from the dead, ascended into\nHeaven, and sits at the right hand of God the Father Almighty; from thence He will come\nto judge the living and the dead.\u201d\nSlide 5: Our Synopsis of Who is Jesus (6:57)\nJesus Christ is the Son of God and Son of Man, born of the Virgin Mary, and who lived\nin flesh, died for the sins of the world, was buried, rose again, and ascended to the right\nhand of God the Father according to the Scriptures. There He remains until the time that\nhe should return and rule eternal in the new Heaven and the new Earth.\nSlide 6: Who is Jesus? (7:53)\nJesus is BOTH:\n1. Son of God\n2. Son of Man\nSlide 7: Who and What is Jesus? (9:35)\nJesus is one person, two natures.\nHe is one \u201cwho,\u201d two \u201cwhats.\u201d\nTechnical term: incarnation\u2026 The eternal son of God assuming human nature.\nSlide 8: 4 Pillars of the Incarnation (10:25)\nJesus was one person, two natures, but he was so without:\n1. Change\nSlide 9: 4 Pillars of the Incarnation (10:47)\nJesus was one person, two natures, but he was so without:\n1. Change\n2. Confusion\nSlide 10: 4 Pillars of the Incarnation (11:31)\n32\nJesus was one person, two natures, but he was so without:\n1. Change\n2. Confusion\n3. Division\nSlide 11: 4 Pillars of the Incarnation - Division (11:55)\n\u201cThe unique and altogether singular event of the Incarnation of the Son of God does not\nmean that Jesus Christ is part God and part man, nor does it imply that he is the result\nof a confused mixture of the divine and the human. He became truly man while\nremaining truly God. Jesus Christ is true God and true man.\u201d Our Legacy, John D.\nHannah\nSlide 12: 4 Pillars of the Incarnation (12:36)\nJesus was one person, two natures, but he was so without:\n1. Change\n2. Confusion\n3. Division\n4. Separation\nSlide 13: John 1:14 (13:39)\n\u201cAnd the Word became flesh and dwelt among us, and we have seen his glory, glory as\nof the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.\u201d\nSlide 14: Evidence of His Humanity (14:40)\nEvidence of his humanity.\n\u25cf In John 4, Jesus was tired and thirsty and approached the woman at the well for\nwater.\n\u25cf John 11, Jesus wept over Lazarus.\n\u25cf In various other places he showed emotion, fatigue, kindness, humor, anger\nSlide 15: Evidence of His Deity (15:10)\n33\nEvidence of his deity.\n\u25cf High Christologies - Colossians 1, Hebrews 1\n\u25cf John 8:58 - \u201cbefore Abraham was I am.\u201d\n\u25cf John 1:18 - \u201cNo one has ever seen God, but God the One & Only, who is at the\nFather\u2019s side, has made him known.\u201d\n\u25cf Titus 2:13 - \u201cour great God and Savior Jesus Christ\u201d\n\u25cf 2Peter 1:1 - \u201cour God and Savior Jesus Christ\nSlide 16: Philippians 2:5-11 (16:15)\n\u201cHave this mind among yourselves, which is yours in Christ Jesus, who, though he was\nin the form of God, did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but emptied\nhimself, by taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men. And being\nfound in human form, he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death,\neven death on a cross. Therefore God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the\nname that is above every name, so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in\nheaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is\nLord, to the glory of God the Father.\u201d\nSlide 17: Why is it Important that Jesus is Both? (17:01)\nWithout his divinity, Jesus could not be the perfect substitution (sacrifice).\nWithout his humanness, Jesus could not be our high priest (priest).\nSlide 18: The Trilemma (18:49)\n\u201cLet us not say, \u2018I'm ready to accept Jesus as a great moral teacher, but I don't accept\nhis claim to be God.\u2019 That is one thing we must not say. \"A man who was merely a man\nand said the sort of things Jesus said would not be a great moral teacher. He would\neither be a lunatic--on the level with the man who says he is a poached egg-- or else he\nwould be the Devil of Hell. You must make your choice. Either this man was, and is, the\nSon of God: or else a madman or something worse. You can shut Him up for a fool, you\ncan spit at Him and kill Him as a demon; or you can fall at His feet and call Him Lord\nand God. But let us not come with any patronizing nonsense about His being a great\nmoral teacher. He has not left that open to us. He did not intend to.\u201d C.S. Lewis\nSlide 19: Acts 2:36 (19:36)\n34\n\u201cLet all the house of Israel therefore know for certain that God has made him both Lord\nand Christ, this Jesus whom you crucified.\u201d\nSlide 20: Errant Beliefs (20:05)\n\u25cf Ebionism (early Jews) - only human\n\u25cf Docetism (greeks / gentiles) - only divine\n\u25cf Adoptionism - becomes divine\n\u25cf Modalism - one person\n\u25cf Arianiam - divine creation\n\u25cf Apollinariainism - Human shell\n\u25cf Nestorianism - split nature\n\u25cf Eutychianism - merged nature\nSlide 21: Christological Orthodoxy (21:55)\n1. Pre-Existence\n2. Virgin Birth\n3. Consciousness of divine sonship\n4. Performed literal miracles\n5. Foreknowledge of and execution of expiatory death\n6. Bodily resurrection\n7. Future Physical return to earth\nSlide 22: Pre-Incarnation (23:30)\nAs a person of the trinity, Jesus was not born of God the Father and therefore created.\nHe has been eternally past and will be eternally present.\nSlide 23: Pre-Incarnation and the Roles of Jesus (24:08)\n1. Vehicle of Creation for the Universe (Col. 1:16-17).\n2. Lord of the Spirit (John 15:26, 16:14).\n3. Jesus reveals the Father (Heb.1).\n4. The Lamb that was slain before the foundation of the world (Rev. 5:9).\nSlide 24: Incarnation (25:39)\n35\n\u201cSo that two whole, perfect, and distinct Natures, the Godhead and the manhood, were\ninseparably joined together in one person, without conversion, composition, or\nconfusion. Which person is very God and very man, yet one Christ, the only mediator\nbetween God and man\u201d Westminster Confession, Article VIII.2.\nSlide 25: Post-Resurrection (26:52)\nWe know that Jesus had a bodily resurrection.\nWe know that:\n1. The tomb was empty (John 20:1-10)\n2. That he appeared to his disciples (Luke 24:36-49, John 21:14)\n3. He confronted Thomas about the scars in his hands and feet (John 20:14)\n4. He ate breakfast with Peter (John 21:15)\nSlide 26: Post-Resurrection (27:15)\nWe know that Jesus ascended heavenly (Acts 1)\nWe know that Jesus is eternally both the Son of God and the Son of Man (Rev. 4-5)\n36\nSession 7: Jesus Pt 2 (Josh)\nTeacher: Brett Younker :05\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology7 (:09)\nSlide 1: John 14:9 (1:00)\n\u201cAnyone who has seen me has seen the father.\u201d\nSlide 2: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully Man? (2:10)\n1. He was born (Luke 1:34). (2:14)\nSlide 3: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully Man? (2:24)\n1. He was born (Luke 1:34).\n2. He grew (Luke 2:52).\nSlide 4: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully Man? (2:37)\n1. He was born (Luke 1:34).\n2. He grew (Luke 2:52).\n3. He was hungry and tired (Matt. 21:18; John 4:6).\nSlide 5: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully Man? (3:06)\n1. He was born (Luke 1:34).\n2. He grew (Luke 2:52).\n4. He was hungry and tired (Matt. 21:18; John 4:6).\n3. He was tempted (Luke 4:2).\nSlide 6: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully Man? (3:36)\n1. He was born (Luke 1:34).\n2. He grew (Luke 2:52).\n7 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n37\n5. He was hungry and tired (Matt. 21:18; John 4:6).\n3. He was tempted (Luke 4:2).\n4. He died (Mark 15:37).\nSlide 7: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (4:17)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\nSlide 8: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (4:44)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\n2. He was aware of his divine sonship (Luke 2:41-52).\nSlide 9: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (5:17)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\n2. He was aware of his divine sonship (Luke 2:41-52).\n3. He forgives sin (Matt. 9:2-7).\nSlide 10: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (6:04)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\n2. He was aware of his divine sonship (Luke 2:41-52).\n3. He forgives sin (Matt. 9:2-7).\n4. He performed miracles (Matt. 14:13-21).\nSlide 11: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (7:18)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\n2. He was aware of his divine sonship (Luke 2:41-52).\n3. He forgives sin (Matt. 9:2-7).\n4. He performed miracles (Matt. 14:13-21).\n5. He overcame temptation (Luke 4:1-11).\nSlide 12: How Do We Know that Jesus was Fully God? (7:57)\n1. He claimed to be God (John 10:31).\n2. He was aware of his divine sonship (Luke 2:41-52).\n3. He forgives sin (Matt. 9:2-7).\n4. He performed miracles (Matt. 14:13-21).\n38\n5. He overcame temptation (Luke 4:1-11).\n6. He knew his purpose (Matt. 16:21).\nSlide 13: 2 Corinthians 5:21 (9:57)\n\u201cGod made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the\nrighteousness of God.\u201d\nSlide 14: Romans 5:18-19 (12:23)\n\u201cConsequently, just as one trespass resulted in condemnation for all people, so also one\nrighteous act resulted in justification and life for all people. For just as through the\ndisobedience of the one man the many were made sinners, so also through the\nobedience of the one man the many will be made righteous.\u201d\nSlide 15: High Christologies in Scripture: (14:54)\n\u201cIn the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God. He\nwas with God in the beginning. Through him all things were made; without him nothing\nwas made that has been made. In him was life, and that life was the light of all mankind.\nThe light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcomeit\u2026\u201d (John 1:1-5).\nSlide 16: High Christologies in Scripture: (15:14)\n\u201cThe true light that gives light to everyone was coming into the world. He was in the\nworld, and though the world was made through him, the world did not recognize him. He\ncame to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him. Yet to all who did\nreceive him, to those who believed in his name, he gave the right to become children of\nGod\u2014 children born not of natural descent, nor of human decision or a husband\u2019s will,\nbut born of God. The Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us. We have\nseen his glory, the glory of the one and only Son, who came from the Father, full of grace\nand truth\u201d (John 1:9-14).\nSlide 17: High Christologies in Scripture: (16:49)\n\u201cThe Son is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn over all creation. For in him all\nthings were created: things in heaven and on earth, visible and invisible, whether thrones\nor powers or rulers or authorities; all things have been created through him and for him.\nHe is before all things, and in him all things hold together. And he is the head of the\n39\nbody, the church; he is the beginning and the firstborn from among the dead, so that in\neverything he might have the supremacy. For God was pleased to have all his fullness\ndwell in him, and through him to reconcile to himself all things, whether things on earth\nor things in heaven, by making peace through his blood, shed on the cross\u201d (Col.1:15-19).\nSlide 18: High Christologies in Scripture: (19:10)\n\u201c Who, being in very natureGod, did not consider equality with God something to be used\nto his own advantage; rather, he made himself nothing by taking the very nature of a\nservant, being made in human likeness. And being found in appearance as a man, he\nhumbled himself by becoming obedient to death\u2014even death on a cross!\u201d (Phil. 2:5-8).\nSlide 19: High Christologies in Scripture: (19:58)\n\u201cTherefore God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above\nevery name, that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth\nand under the earth, and every tongue acknowledge that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the\nglory of God the Father\u201d (Phil. 2:5-8).\nSlide 20: High Christologies in Scripture: (20:36)\n\u201cIn the past God spoke to our ancestors through the prophets at many times and in\nvarious ways, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son, whom he appointed\nheir of all things, and through whom also he made the universe. The Son is the radiance\nof God\u2019s glory and the exact representation of his being, sustaining all things by his\npowerful word. After he had provided purification for sins, he sat down at the right hand\nof the Majesty in heaven\u201d (Heb. 1:1-3).\nSlide 21: What Jesus Came to Teach: (21:58)\n\u201cFor God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son, that whoever believes in\nhim shall not perish but have eternal life\u201d (John 3:16).\nSlide 22: What Jesus Came to Teach: (22:31)\n\u25cf The reality of the Kingdom of God (Matt. 5-7).\nSlide 23: What Jesus Came to Teach: (25:33)\n\u25cf The reality of the Kingdom of God (Matt. 5-7).\n\u25cf That the Kingdom of God is present and future (Matt. 11:11).\n40\nSlide 24: What Jesus Came to Teach: (26:25)\n\u25cf The reality of the Kingdom of God (Matt. 5-7).\n\u25cf That the Kingdom of God is present and future (Matt. 11:11).\n\u25cf That He would send His Holy Spirit (John 14:16-17).\n41\nSession 8: Salvation Pt 1 - V2 (Jake)\nTeacher: Emily Draa\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 |\nSalvation, Part 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology8\nSlide 1: What is salvation? (0:52)\nSalvation is the redemptive plan of God by grace alone, through faith alone, in Christ\nalone, by the power of the Holy Spirit.\nSlide 2: Salvation is by grace alone (1:11)\nSalvation is unearned love. We did nothing to deserve it.\nIt was initiated, activated, and achieved by God.\nSlide 3: What is salvation? (1:27)\nSalvation is a rescue, a right-standing, and a renewal.\n\u25cf Rescue: justification through atonement.\n\u25cf Right-standing: imputed righteousness as a new creation.\n\u25cf Renewal: Spirit-filled sanctification leading to future glorification.\nSlide 4: Romans 8:28-30 (2:20)\n\u201cAnd we know that for those who love God all things work together for good, for those\nwho are called according to his purpose. For those whom he foreknew he also\npredestined to be conformed to the image of his Son, in order that he might be the\nfirstborn among many brothers. And those whom he predestined he also called, and\nthose whom he called he also justified, and those whom he justified he also glorified\u201d\n(italics added)\nSlide 5: Salvation is Past, Present, and Future (3:10)\n\u201cFor by a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified\u201d\n(Heb. 10:14).\n8 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n42\nSlide 6: The Primary Terms of Salvation, Part 1 (4:09)\n1. Depravity\n2. The Judgement\n3. The Atonement (Propitiation)\nSlide 7: Depravity (4:24)\nDepravity is the lynchpin for your understanding of your need for a Savior.\nDepravity posits that we are ALL sinners in need of the mercy of God\nSlide 8: Romans 3:10-13 (5:55)\n\"There is none righteous, not even one; there is none who understands, there is none\nwho seeks for god; all have turned aside, together they have become useless; there is\nnone who does good, there is not even one.\"\nSlide 9: Tim Keller\u2019s Approach to Romans 3 (6:21)\nHow sin affects sinner:\n\u25cf Our legal standing (3:10)\n\u25cf Our minds (3:11)\n\u25cf Our motives (3:11b)\n\u25cf Our wills (3:12)\n\u25cf Our tongues (3:13-14)\n\u25cf Our relationships with others (3:15-17)\n\u25cf Our relationship with God (3:18)\nSlide 10: Romans 5:12 (7:01)\n\u201cTherefore, just as sin came into the world through one man, and death through sin, and\nso death spread to all men because all sinned\u2014\u201d\nSlide 11: Recap of Depravity (7:11)\nDepravity means that we have all sinned, we have all been separated from God.\nThere is no escaping it, and we are all deserving of judgment.\n43\nSlide 12: Judgment (7:23)\nWhat is the core issue demanding salvation? God\u2019s righteous judgment.\nWhat is he judging? Sin.\nSlide 13: Judgment (8:27)\nGod does not want people to perish.\n\u201cGod has no pleasure in the death of the wicked\u201d (Ezek. 33:11).\nSlide 14: Judgment before the Cross (8:50)\nBefore the cross, we know from Scripture that God instituted the sacrificial system as\n\u201ctemporary acts of atonement.\u201d This was a system of one-time, acceptable, but not\neternally effectual payments for the wages of sin.\nSlide 15: The Blood as Atonement (9:18)\n\u201cFor the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it for you on the altar to make\natonement for your souls, for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life\u201d (Lev.\n17:11).\nSlide 16: The Old Testament Sacrificial System (10:47)\nThe Old Testament Sacrificial System shows us the following realities of our sin and\nGod\u2019s salvation.\n1. The incredible, patient, and forgiving mercy of the Lord towards sinners.\nSlide 17: The Old Testament Sacrificial System (11:08)\nThe Old Testament Sacrificial System shows us the following realities of our sin and\nGod\u2019s salvation.\n1. The incredible, patient, and forgiving mercy of the Lord towards sinners.\n2. The uncompromising Holiness of God.\nSlide 18: The Old Testament Sacrificial System (11:19)\nThe Old Testament Sacrificial System shows us the following realities of our sin and\nGod\u2019s salvation.\n44\n1. The incredible, patient, and forgiving mercy of the Lord towards sinners.\n2. The uncompromising Holiness of God.\n3. The inability of flawed sinners to earn acceptance with God on their own merit.\nSlide 19: The Old Testament Sacrificial System (11:27)\nThe Old Testament Sacrificial System shows us the following realities of our sin and\nGod\u2019s salvation.\n1. The incredible, patient, and forgiving mercy of the Lord towards sinners.\n2. The uncompromising Holiness of God.\n3. The inability of flawed sinners to earn acceptance with God on their own merit.\n4. The need for a once-for-all sacrifice that extends God's mercy without\ncompromising His Justice.\nSlide 20: Atonement and Propitiation (12:00)\nIn Romans 3:25 and Hebrews 9:5, the Greek word \u2018hilasterion\u2019 is used. It is the word\nemployed by the Septuagint translators in Exodus 25:17 and elsewhere as the\nequivalent for the Hebrew \u2018kapporeth\u2019 , which means \"covering,\" and is used of the lid of\nthe ark of the covenant (Exodus 25:21 ; 30:6).\nSlide 21: Substitutionary Atonement (12:35)\nSubstitutionary atonement - Jesus Christ through his bloodshed took the full punishment\nthat we deserved for our sins as a substitute in our place.\nSlide 22: 5 Major Views of Atonement (12:55)\n1. Ransom Theory - God owes satan a debt (satan holds humanity captive) so\nChrist came to fulfill that debt.\nSlide 23: 5 Major Views of Atonement (13:13)\n1. Ransom Theory\n2. Substitution Theory - God\u2019s honor is offended by our sin and humanity can never\nrepay it. Therefore, Christ came to atone for humanity and restore God\u2019s honor.\nSlide 24: 5 Major Views of Atonement (13:26)\n1. Ransom Theory\n45\n2. Substitution Theory\n3. Penal Substitution Theory - It wasn\u2019t just God\u2019s honor that was offended - our sin\ndemanded payment. Therefore, Christ came in humanity as our atonement to\npay the wage of sin.\nSlide 25: 5 Major Views of Atonement (13:50)\n1. Ransom Theory\n2. Substitution Theory\n3. Penal Substitution Theory\n4. Moral Influence Theory - Christ\u2019s love, life, death, and resurrection show\nhumanity an example that morally influences us to become better and more\nrighteous before God.\nSlide 26: 5 Major Views of Atonement (14:26)\n1. Ransom Theory\n2. Substitution Theory\n3. Penal Substitution Theory\n4. Moral Influence Theory\n5. Christus Victor Theory - emphasizes the triumph of Christ over the evil powers of\nthe world. Mainly view Christ as a conqueror.\n46\nSession 9: Salvation Pt. 2. V2 (Jake)\nTeacher: Emily Draa\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology9\nSlide 1: Primary Terms of Salvation, Part 1 (0:20)\n1. Depravity\n2. Judgment\n3. Atonement\nSlide 2: Primary Terms of Salvation, Part 2 (0:43)\n1. Justification\n2. Imputed Righteousness\n3. Sanctification\nSlide 3: Justification (0:49)\nThis is the beginning of the literal salvation process\nWe have been justified by grace through faith.\nSlide 4: Justification (1:09)\nJustification is a declaration of righteousness over our lives.\n\u25cf \u201cto pronounce, accept, and treat as just.\"\nSlide 5: Justification (1:20)\n\u201cIt is thus a forensic term, denoting a judicial act of administering the law - in this case,\nby declaring a verdict of acquittal, and so excluding all possibility of condemnation.\nJustification thus settles the legal status of the person justified.\u201d J.I. Packer\nSlide 6: Justification (1:41)\n9 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n47\nJustification does not just declare someone innocent - justification declares someone\nrighteous.\nSlide 7: Imputed Righteousness (2:38)\nImputed righteousness is the concept that Christ\u2019s righteousness is imputed or credited\nto us.\nSlide 8: Sanctification (4:44)\n\u201cAnd such were some of you. But you were washed, you were sanctified, you were\njustified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ and by the Spirit of our God\u201d (1 Cor. 6:11).\nSlide 9: Sanctification (5:15)\nSanctification is the process by which we become more like Jesus.\nSlide 10: Why Salvation is Important to You? (5:51)\n\u25cf Salvation is what reconnects us in relationship with the Father.\n\u25cf The process of salvation brings restoration to what was broken.\n\u25cf Salvation gives us peace, purpose and a hope in a broken world.\nSlide 11: Salvation\u2019s Tensions (7:35)\n\u25cf Election and predestination\n\u25cf How can I know if I\u2019m saved?\n\u25cf Can I lose my salvation?\nSlide 12: Election and Predestination (8:18)\n\u201ceven as he chose us in him before the foundation of the world, that we should be holy\nand blameless before him. In love he predestined us for adoption to himself as sons\nthrough Jesus Christ, according to the purpose of his will,\u201d (Eph. 1:4).\nSlide 13: Election and Predestination (8:41)\n48\n\u201cBut we ought always to give thanks to God for you, brothers beloved by the Lord,\nbecause God chose you as the firstfruits to be saved, through sanctification by the Spirit\nand belief in the truth\u201d (2 Thess. 2:13)\nSlide 14: Election and Predestination (9:32)\nElection: This word is taken from the Scriptures that refer to believers as \u201cthe Elect\u201d, or\neklektos. There are several verses where the word eklektos is used (a few examples\nare below):\n\u25cf Romans 8:33\n\u25cf Titus 1:1\n\u25cf Colossians 3:12\nSlide 15: How Can God Hold People Accountable? (10:54)\n\u201cFor the mind that is set on the flesh is hostile to God, for it does not submit to God's\nlaw; indeed, it cannot\u201d (Rom. 8:7).\n\u201cThe natural person does not accept the things of the Spirit of God, for they are folly to\nhim, and he is not able to understand them because they are spiritually discerned\u201d (1\nCor. 2:14).\nSlide 16: How Can God Hold People Accountable? (11:22)\n\u201cFor the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and\nunrighteousness of men, who by their unrighteousness suppress the truth. For what can\nbe known about God is plain to them, because God has shown it to them. For his\ninvisible attributes, namely, his eternal power and divine nature, have been clearly\nperceived, ever since the creation of the world, in the things that have been made. So\nthey are without excuse\u201d (Rom. 1:18-20).\nSlide 17: How Can God Hold People Accountable? (12:13)\nIf you are saved, your salvation should provide you an unending sense of awe. God\nsaved you. He knew all the days of your life before there was one (Psalm 139:16) wrote\nyour name in the book of life (Luke 10:20, Philippians 4:3).\nSlide 18: Why Do We Evangelize? (12:30)\nWe evangelize because:\n1. We don\u2019t know who is and isn\u2019t elect.\n49\n2. Jesus evangelized while on Earth.\n3. Therefore, we follow in his example\nSlide 19: How Do You Have Confidence in Your Salvation? (13:39)\nHas the Gospel come to you?\n\u201cFor we know, brothers loved by God, that he has chosen you, because our gospel\ncame to you not only in word, but also in power and in the Holy Spirit and with full\nconviction\u201d (1 Thess. 1:4-5a).\nSlide 20: How Do You Have Confidence in Your Salvation? (14:29)\nLook at the fruit of your life:\n\u25cf Do you have conviction over your sins?\n\u25cf Are you actively pursuing putting to death sin and aligning more with holiness?\n\u25cf Are you growing in intimacy with the Lord? Are you more trusting, more\ndependent, more reliant on Him?\n\u25cf Are you growing quicker to repent of your sin?\n\u25cf Are you eager to say - \u201cJesus is Lord?\u201d\nSlide 21: Eternal Security and Losing Salvation (16:00)\n\u201cFor those whom he foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his\nSon, in order that he might be the firstborn among many brothers. And those whom he\npredestined he also called, and those whom he called he also justified, and those whom\nhe justified he also glorified\u201d (Rom. 8:29-30)\nSlide 22: Eternal Security and Losing Salvation (17:22)\n\u201cAnd we desire each one of you to show the same earnestness to have the full\nassurance of hope until the end,\u201d (Heb. 6:11).\n\u201cI give them eternal life, and they will never perish, and no one will snatch them out of\nmy hand\u201d (John 10:28).\n50\n51\nSession 10: Sanctification (Emma)\nTeacher: Emily Vogeltanz\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology10\nSlide 1: Sanctification (1:36)\nSanctification is the already (being saved), but not yet (being perfected).\nSlide 2: Sanctification (2:48)\nSanctification is both the position and the process that begins the moment we put our\nfaith in Jesus.\nIt is present and promised renewal of our hearts and lives from the inside and out.\nIt is the process of becoming more like Jesus every single day.\nSlide 3: Why is sanctification important? (3:36)\n1. Process\n2. Purpose\n3. Confidence\nSlide 4: Why is sanctification important? (3:48)\n1. Sanctification is the process of how we are refined into the image of Christ.\nSlide 5: Why is sanctification important? (3:55)\n1. Sanctification is the process of how we are refined into the image of Christ.\n2. Sanctification gives us the purpose of being an ambassador of the Gospel.\n10 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n52\nSlide 6: Why is sanctification important? (4:08)\n1. Sanctification is the process of how we are refined into the image of Christ.\n2. Sanctification gives us the purpose of being an ambassador of the Gospel.\n3. Sanctification gives us this confidence in our new identity, that we are now\ncalled sons and daughters of God and co-heirs with Christ.\nSlide 7: This confidence allows us to: (4:20)\n\u25cf fight back against fear.\n\u25cf reject the ways of the world while embracing the ways of Christ.\n\u25cf boldly proclaim our faith.\n\u25cf wisely make use of our days.\n\u25cf live for what matters most.\nSlide 8: The Extended Middle (4:47)\n\u201c\u201cThe extended middle\u201d is the space between justification and glorification.\u201d Roy Zuck\nSlide 9: Sanctification is positional (5:44)\nOur position is in Christ Jesus.\nSlide 10: Sanctification is positional (5:54)\n\u201cTherefore, if anyone is in Christ, he is a new creation. The old has passed away;\nbehold, the new has come.\u201d (2 Cor 5:17)\nSlide 11: A New Authority (6:07)\n\u25cf We have moved from death to life (Rom. 6, 8)\n\u25cf We have a new identity (Rom. 8)\n\u25cf We live in freedom (Rom. 8:1-2)\n\u25cf We have moved from being under the law to under the Spirit (Rom. 8:3-4)\n\u25cf We don\u2019t have to obey sin but now can obey God (Rom. 6)\n\u25cf We can be transformed by the renewing of our minds (Rom. 12:2)\nSlide 12: Sanctification is Positional (6:50)\n53\n\u201cFor by grace you have been saved through faith. And this is not your own doing; it is\nthe gift of God, not a result of works, so that no one may boast. For we are his\nworkmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand,\nthat we should walk in them\u201d (Eph 2:8-10).\nSlide 13: Sanctification is Progressive (7:25)\nWe are becoming more and more like Christ.\nSanctification is a continual renewal and transformation by the Spirit of God fulfilling the\npromise to complete the work He started in us.\nSlide 14: Sanctification is Progressive (8:50)\n\u201cFor by one sacrifice he has made perfect forever those who are being made holy\u201d (Heb\n10:14).\nSlide 15: Key Takeways from Sanctification (9:38)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\nSlide 16: Sanctification is a combination of faith and works (9:57)\n\u25cf Salvation is by grace through faith in Christ Jesus (Positional)\n\u25cf The evidence of our faith is the presence of good works (Progressive).\nSlide 17: Key Takeways from Sanctification (11:33)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\nSlide 18: Philippians 3:10-12 (11:48)\n\u201cthat I may know him and the power of his resurrection, and may share his sufferings,\nbecoming like him in his death, that by any means possible I may attain the resurrection\nfrom the dead. Not that I have already obtained this or am already perfect, but I press\non to make it my own, because Christ Jesus has made me his own.\u201d\nSlide 19: Key Takeways from Sanctification (12:50)\n54\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\n3. The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer.\nSlide 20: The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer (13:16)\n\u201cBesides this you know the time, that the hour has come for you to wake from sleep.\nFor salvation is nearer to us now than when we first believed.\u201d (Rom 13:11).\nSlide 21: Key Takeways from Sanctification (13:46)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\n3. The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer.\n4. Sanctification means that you live with a new identity.\nSlide 22: 2 Corinthians 5:21 (14:46)\n\u201cFor our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become\nthe righteousness of God.\u201d\nSlide 23: Colossians 1:12-14 (15:03)\n\u201cGive thanks to the Father, who has qualified you to share in the inheritance of the\nsaints in light. He has delivered us from the domain of darkness and transferred us to\nthe kingdom of his beloved Son, in whom we have redemption, the forgiveness of sins.\u201d\nSlide 24: Key Takeways from Sanctification (15:30)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\n3. The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer.\n4. Sanctification means that you live with a new identity.\n5. Sanctification means that our goal is that we are constantly moving towards\nbeing conformed to the image of Christ.\nSlide 25: Evidence of being conformed into the image of Christ (16:57)\n\u25cf We become more confident in our identity as sons and daughters of God\n(Romans 8:16-17).\n55\n\u25cf We become more glorious, moving from one degree of glory to another as we\nconsider the light of the Glory of the knowledge of Christ (2 Corinthians 3:18-4:6).\n\u25cf We become more intolerant of sin and the passions of the flesh (Romans 8:13)\n\u25cf We become more courageous, less fearful, and more assured through\nuncertainty (Romans 8:14-15).\n\u25cf We become more content in our sufferings, knowing that we have hope in the\nmidst of hardship (Romans 8:18)\nSlide 26: Key Takeways from Sanctification (18:26)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\n3. The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer.\n4. Sanctification means that you live with a new identity.\n5. Sanctification means that our goal is that we are constantly moving towards\nbeing conformed to the image of Christ.\n6. Sanctification means we have new purpose: to be ambassadors of Christ.\nSlide 27: 2 Corinthians 5:20 (18:34)\n\u201cTherefore, we are ambassadors for Christ, God making his appeal through us.\u201d\nSlide 28: Key Takeways from Sanctification (19:34)\n1. Sanctification is a combination of faith and works.\n2. Sanctification shows us the joyful reality of past, present, and future salvation.\n3. The eternal reality of salvation is drawing closer.\n4. Sanctification means that you live with a new identity.\n5. Sanctification means that our goal is that we are constantly moving towards\nbeing conformed to the image of Christ.\n6. Sanctification means we have new purpose: to be ambassadors of Christ.\n7. Sanctification allows us to learn to differentiate between the fruit of the spirit and\nfruit of the flesh.\nSlide 29: Fruit of the Spirit (19:51)\n\u201cBut the fruits of the Spirit is love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness,\nfaithfulness, gentleness, self-control, against such things there is no law\u201d (Gal 5:22-23).\n56\nSubsection: Sanctification allows us to learn to differentiate between the fruit of the spirit\nand fruit of the flesh\nSlide 30: Fruit of the Flesh (20:04)\n\u201cNow the works of the flesh are evident: sexual immorality, impurity, sensuality, idolatry,\nsorcery, enmity, strife, jealousy, fits of anger, rivalries, disensions, divisions, envy,\ndrunkenness, orgies, and things like these.\u201d (Gal 5:19-21)\nSubsection: Sanctification allows us to learn to differentiate between the fruit of the spirit\nand fruit of the flesh\nSlide 31: Galatians 5:16 and 5:24 (20:42)\n\u201cBut I say, walk by the Spirit, and you will not gratify the desires of the flesh.\u201d\n\u201cAnd those who belong to Christ Jesus have crucified the flesh with its passions and\ndesires.\u201d\nSlide 33: Romans 7:21-25 (21:52)\n\u201cSo I find it to be a law that when I want to do right, evil lies close at hand. For I delight\nin the law of God, in my inner being, but I see in my members another law waging war\nagainst the law of my mind and making me captive to the law of sin that dwells in my\nmembers. Wretched man that I am! Who will deliver me from this body of death?\nThanks be to God through Jesus Christ our Lord.\u201d\nSlide 34: The Holy Spirit (23:54)\nSanctification is not possible without the person of the Holy Spirit and his power,\nguidance, assurance, and help in our lives. That is why we often say that sanctification\nis predicated on the indwelling of the Holy Spirit of God in our lives.\nSlide 35: The Holy Spirit (24:20)\n\u25cf Opens our eyes to see Jesus\n\u25cf Opens our ears to hear and receive the gospel\n\u25cf Empowers us to walk through this life and pursue holiness\nSlide 36: Sanctification Personally Applied (27:00)\n57\n1. Get baptized.\n2. Join a local church.\n3. Pursue accountability.\n4. Read the Scriptures together.\n5. Live holy and pure as examples to one another.\n58\nSession 11: The Church (Josh)\nTeacher: Grant Partrick\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology11 (00:07)\nSlide 1: The Church (1:45)\nFaith is personal but it is not meant to be individual.\nSlide 2: The Church (2:10)\n\u201cEverywhere where spiritual growth is mentioned in the New Testament, it is mentioned\nin the context of community.\u201d - Ben Stuart\nSlide 3: What is the Church and What is It\u2019s Purpose? (3:08)\nWe believe that those who have placed their faith in Christ are knit together in one Body,\nthe Church, a distinctive community of faith expressed in local clusters, engaging\nculture on every front with God\u2019s hope and love \u2026 a Church for which Christ will\npersonally return.\nSlide 4: The Church (3:36)\nThe Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\nThe Church centralizes around the pillars of community, teaching, prayer, and the\nsacraments (Acts 2:42).\nSlide 5: The Church (3:57)\nThe true body of Christ is the one, holy, global, and gospel-centered church, called by God the\nFather, united in Christ, and preserved by the Spirit. A true Christian congregation is centered\non Christ\u2019s person and work, governed by the Holy Scriptures, conformed to the ancient\ntradition, identified by particular apostolic marks and works, and free from heresy.\n11 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n59\nSlide 6: Overview of our Study on \u2018The Church\u2019 (5:16)\n1. What is the Church and what is it\u2019s purpose?\n2. What is the purpose of joining or belonging to a Church?\n3. How does the Church help the believer grow in sanctification?\nSlide 7: The Church (5:40)\nIt is the tangible expression of Christ\u2019s work on planet earth; a unified body of believers\nrepresenting Christ\u2019s value and doing Christ\u2019s work.\nSlide 8: Our Definition of The Church (6:23)\nThe Church (Ekkl\u0113sia) - the people of God, becoming like Jesus, empowered by the Spirit\ntowards the mission of glorifying God.\nSlide 9: Where Did the Church Come From? (7:03)\n\u201cWhen Jesus came to the region of Caesarea Philippi, he asked his disciples, \u201cWho do\npeople say the Son of Man is?\u201d They replied, \u201cSome say John the Baptist; others say\nElijah; and still others, Jeremiah or one of the prophets.\u201d \u201cBut what about you?\u201d he\nasked. \u201cWho do you say I am?\u201d Simon Peter answered, \u201cYou are the Messiah, the Son of\nthe living God.\u201d Jesus replied, \u201cBlessed are you, Simon son of Jonah, for this was not\nrevealed to you by flesh and blood, but by my Father in heaven. And I tell you that you\nare Peter, and on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not\novercome it. I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven; whatever you bind on\nearth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven\u201d\n(Matthew 16:13-19).\nSlide 10: Where Did the Church Come From? (8:04)\n\u201cWhen the day of Pentecost came, they were all together in one place. Suddenly a sound\nlike the blowing of a violent wind came from heaven and filled the whole house where\nthey were sitting. They saw what seemed to be tongues of fire that separated and came\nto rest on each of them. All of them were filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak in\nother tongues as the Spirit enabled them\u201d (Acts 2:1-4).\nSlide 11: Where Did the Church Come From? (9:32)\n\u201cConsequently, you are no longer foreigners and strangers, but fellow citizens with God\u2019s\npeople and also members of his household, built on the foundation of the apostles and\n60\nprophets, with Christ Jesus himself as the chief cornerstone. In him the whole building\nis joined together and rises to become a holy temple in the Lord. And in him you too are\nbeing built together to become a dwelling in which God lives by his Spirit\u201d (Ephesians\n2:19-22).\nSlide 12: Where Did the Church Come From? (10:19)\nBreakdown of the Early Church:\n\u25cf Apostle Era = 33 A.D - 100 A.D\n\u25cf The Earliest Churchmen Era = 100 A.D - 150 A.D\n\u25cf The Bishop + Apologist Era = 150 A.D - 300 A.D\n\u25cf The Council Era = 300 A.D - 600 A.D\nSlide 13: Where Did the Church Come From? (10:59)\nThe Apostle Era (33 A.D - 100 A.D) was about \u201cAccurate Testimony\u201d (2 Pet. 1:16).\nSlide 14: Where Did the Church Come From? (11:55)\nThe Earliest Churcmen Era (100 A.D - 150 A.D) was about \u201cAccurate Training.\u201d\nSlide 15: Where Did the Church Come From? (12:54)\nThe Bishop + Apologist Era (150 A.D - 300 A.D) was about \u201cAccurate Teaching.\u201d\nSlide 16: Where Did the Church Come From? (13:33)\nThe Council Era (300 A.D - 600 A.D) was about \u201cAccurate Theology.\u201d\nSlide 17: Overview of our Study on \u2018The Church\u2019 (14:56)\n1. What is the Church and what is it\u2019s purpose?\n2. What is the purpose of joining or belonging to a Church?\n3. How does the Church help the believer grow in sanctification?\nSlide 18: What is the purpose of joining or belonging to a Church? (15:12)\nSix Reasons Why Belonging to a Local Church is Necessary:\n1. It widens our perspective of God.\n2. It clarifies our purpose.\n3. It protects us from errors.\n4. It reminds us of God\u2019s faithfulness.\n61\n5. It builds our confidence in the future.\n6. It anchors our beliefs.\nSlide 19: The Church and Sanctification (16:20)\nThe Marks + Works of the Church (Dr. Michael Svigel, DTS):\n\u25cf Marks - What the Church believes\n\u25cf Works - What the Church does\nSlide 20: The Church and Sanctification (16:55)\nThe Marks: Orthodoxy, Order, and Ordinances\n\u25cf Orthodoxy - Right Teaching\n\u25cf Order - Right Shepherding\n\u25cf Ordinances/Sacraments - Right Alignment\nSlide 21: The Church and Sanctification (18:42)\nOrdinances: Baptism + The Lord\u2019s Supper\n\u25cf Baptism - A public declaration of an inward transformation.\nSlide 22: The Church and Sanctification (19:53)\nOrdinances: Baptism + The Lord\u2019s Supper\n\u25cf Communion/The Lord\u2019s Supper/The Eucharist - A recentering on the person\nand work of Jesus; a consistent remembrance of what He has done.\nSlide 23: The Church and Sanctification (20:29)\nWorks of the Church: Evangelism\n\u25cf Evangelism - the practice of embracing Jesus\u2019 call to make disciples by sharing\nthe good news about His life, death, burial, and resurrection\n62\nSlide 24: The Church and Sanctification (22:12)\nWorks of the Church: Evangelism\n\u201cFor the Scripture says, \u201cEveryone who believes in him will not be put to shame.\u201d For\nthere is no distinction between Jew and Greek; for the same Lord is Lord of all,\nbestowing his riches on all who call on him. For \u201ceveryone who calls on the name of the\nLord will be saved.\u201d How then will they call on him in whom they have not believed? And\nhow are they to believe in him of whom they have never heard? And how are they to\nhear without someone preaching? And how are they to preach unless they are sent? As\nit is written, \u201cHow beautiful are the feet of those who preach the good news!\u201d (Romans\n10:11-15).\nSlide 25: The Church and Sanctification (23:21)\nWorks of the Church: Discipleship\n\u25cf Discipleship - Growing in Christlikeness.\nSlide 26: The Church and Sanctification (24:18)\nWorks of the Church: Worship\n\u25cf Worship - Responding to God for who He is and what He has done.\nSlide 27: The Church and Sanctification (24:33)\n\u201cTherefore, I urge you, brothers and sisters, in view of God\u2019s mercy, to offer your bodies\nas a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God\u2014this is your true and proper worship\u201d\n(Rom. 12:1).\nSlide 28: The Marks + Works of the Church (25:17)\n\u25cf Marks: Orthodoxy, Order, and Ordinances\n\u25cf Works: Evangelism, Discipleship (Edification), and Worship (Exaltation)\nSlide 29: The Church (25:34)\n63\nThe Church is the people of God, becoming like Jesus, empowered by the Spirit\ntowards the mission of glorifying God.\nSlide 30: Key Takeaways: (25:50)\n1. The Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\nSlide 31: Key Takeaways: (25:58)\n1. The Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\n2. The Church centralizes around the pillars of community, teaching, prayer, and the\nsacraments.\nSlide 32: Key Takeaways: (26:09)\n1. The Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\n2. The Church centralizes around the pillars of community, teaching, prayer, and the\nsacraments.\n3. God never intended for us to live out our faith alone.\nSlide 33: Key Takeaways: (26:21)\n1. The Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\n2. The Church centralizes around the pillars of community, teaching, prayer, and the\nsacraments.\n3. God never intended for us to live out our faith alone.\n4. The Church allows us to grow deeper and accomplish the will of God on Earth as it is in\nHeaven.\nSlide 34: Key Takeaways: 26:34)\n1. The Church is meant to accomplish the unbeatable plan of Christ on this Earth and is\npurposed to make disciples of all nations.\n2. The Church centralizes around the pillars of community, teaching, prayer, and the\nsacraments.\n3. God never intended for us to live out our faith alone.\n4. The Church allows us to grow deeper and accomplish the will of God on Earth as it is in\nHeaven.\n5. The Church is a reflection of what eternity will be.\n64\n65\nSession 12: Eschatology (Josh)\nTeacher: Dr. Aaron Coe\nTitle Slide: Introduction to Essential Theology | The Trinity | Attributes of God |\nBibliology | Humanity + Sin | Jesus, Part 1 | Jesus, Part 2 | Salvation, Part 1 | Salvation,\nPart 2 | Sanctification | The Church | Eschatology12 (00:06)\nSlide 1: Eschatology (01:21)\nEschatology is the study of the \u201clast things.\u201d\nSlide 2: Eschatology (1:37)\nLet what is clear in Scripture inform what is unclear in Scripture.\nSlide 3: What We Know Will Take Place (3:10)\n\u25cf A literal, visible return of Christ.\n\u25cf A bodily resurrection of the saints.\n\u25cf A final judgement.\n\u25cf A literal heaven and literal hell.\nSlide 4: What We Know Will Take Place (4:35)\n1. His return is literal.\n\u201cAfter he said this, he was taken up before their very eyes, and a cloud hid him from their\nsight. They were looking intently up into the sky as he was going, when suddenly two\nmen dressed in white stood beside them. \u201cMen of Galilee,\u201d they said, \u201cwhy do you stand\nhere looking into the sky? This same Jesus, who has been taken from you into heaven,\nwill come back in the same way you have seen him go into heaven\u201d (Acts 1:9-11).\nSlide 5: What We Know Will Take Place (5:26)\n2. His return is in the future.\n12 We want \u201cWho Is God?\u201d to be highlighted on a list of all our topics, indicating which session participants\nare currently watching/progress. We would like this to be a list with one subject/topic/session listed from\ntop-to-bottom.\n66\n\u201cBut about that day or hour no one knows, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son,\nbut only the Father\u201d (Matt. 24:36).\nSlide 6: What We Know Will Take Place (6:24)\n3. Everyone will see Him and bow before Him.\n\u201cBut about that day or hour no one knows, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son,\nbut only the Father\u201d (Matt. 24:36).\nSlide 7: What We Know Will Take Place (6:45)\n\u201cTherefore God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above\nevery name, so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on\nearth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the\nglory of God the Father\u201d (Phil. 2:9-11).\nSlide 8: What We Know Will Take Place (7:52)\nJesus will\u2026\n1. Defeat the powers of evil.\nSlide 9: What We Know Will Take Place (8:07)\nJesus will\u2026\n1. Defeat the powers of evil.\n2. Reverse the curses of sin.\nSlide 10: What We Know Will Take Place (8:29)\nJesus will\u2026\n1. Defeat the powers of evil.\n2. Reverse the curses of sin.\n3. Fulfill His covenants.\nSlide 11: What We Know Will Take Place (8:42)\nJesus will\u2026\n1. Defeat the powers of evil.\n2. Reverse the curses of sin.\n67\n3. Fulfill His covenants.\n4. Restore His creation.\nSlide 12: What We Know Will Take Place (9:15)\nJesus will\u2026\n1. Defeat the powers of evil.\n2. Reverse the curses of sin.\n3. Fulfill His covenants.\n4. Restore His creation.\n5. Live among His people forever.\nSlide 13: Five Events, Four Players, and Two Consequences of Jesus\u2019 Return (12:06)\nFive Events:\n1. Jesus Return (2nd Coming)\n2. The Rapture\n3. The Tribulation\n4. The Millennium\n5. The Eternal Reign\nSlide 14: Five Events, Four Players, and Two Consequences of Jesus\u2019 Return (12:21)\nFour Players:\n1. Jesus\n2. The Church\n3. Israel\n4. Satan\nSlide 15: Five Events, Four Players, and Two Consequences of Jesus\u2019 Return (12:35)\nTwo Consequences:\n1. Eternal life\n2. Eternal death (or separation from God)\nSlide 16: Four Views of The End Times (Revelation 20) (13:34)\n68\n1. Amillennialism - The thousand-year reign of Jesus is figurative (He currently is\nreigning on earth) [Luther, Calvin, Lewis, Sproul, etc.]\nSlide 17: Four Views of The End Times (Revelation 20) (14:19)\n1. Amillennialism - The thousand-year reign of Jesus is figurative (He currently is\nreigning on earth) [Luther, Calvin, Lewis, Sproul, etc.]\n2. Postmillenialism - The thousand-year (literal or figurative) reign of Jesus is\ncoming later [Warfield, Gentry, Leithart].\nSlide 18: Four Views of The End Times (Revelation 20) (14:52)\n1. Amillennialism - The thousand-year reign of Jesus is figurative (He currently is\nreigning on earth) [Luther, Calvin, Lewis, Sproul, etc.]\n2. Postmillenialism - The thousand-year (literal or figurative) reign of Jesus is\ncoming later [Warfield, Gentry, Leithart].\n3. Premillennialism - The thousand-year (literal) reign has not happened yet but will\nhappen in future [Grudem, Gundry, Blomberg].\nSlide 19: Four Views of The End Times (Revelation 20) (15:19)\n1. Amillennialism - The thousand-year reign of Jesus is figurative (He currently is\nreigning on earth) [Luther, Calvin, Lewis, Sproul, etc.]\n2. Postmillenialism - The thousand-year (literal or figurative) reign of Jesus is\ncoming later [Warfield, Gentry, Leithart].\n3. Premillennialism - The thousand-year (literal) reign has not happened yet but will\nhappen in future [Grudem, Gundry, Blomberg].\n4. Dispensationalism - Premillennial view of millennium, emphasizing the\nrelationship between the Church and the nation of Israel [Chafer, Walvoord,\nMacArthur].\nSlide 20: Our Future: Everything will be New. (18:51)\n\u201cAs the new heavens and the new earth that I make will endure before me,\u201d declares the\nLord, \u201cso will your name and descendants endure\u201d (Isa. 66:22).\n\u201cThen I saw \u201ca new heaven and a new earth,\u201d for the first heaven and the first earth had\npassed away\u2026\u201d (Rev. 21:1).\n69\nSlide 21: Our Future: God will Dwell with His People. (20:12)\n\u201cAnd I heard a loud voice from the throne saying, \u201cBehold, the dwelling place of God is\nwith man. He will dwell with them, and they will be his people, and God himself will be\nwith them as their God\u201d (Rev. 21:3).\nSlide 22: Our Future: No more Pain, Sickness, Disease. (20:33)\n\u201cHe will wipe away every tear from their eyes, and death shall be no more, neither shall\nthere be mourning, nor crying, nor pain anymore, for the former things have passed\naway\u201d (Rev. 21:4).\nSlide 23: Our Future: We will have Everything we Need. (21:35)\n\u201cHe said to me: \u201cIt is done. I am the Alpha and the Omega, the Beginning and the End. To\nthe thirsty I will give water without cost from the spring of the water of life\u201d (Rev. 21:6).\nSlide 24: Our Future: Evil People will Not Be There. (21:53)\n\u201cBut the cowardly, the unbelieving, the vile, the murderers, the sexually immoral, those\nwho practice magic arts, the idolaters and all liars\u2014they will be consigned to the fiery\nlake of burning sulfur. This is the second death\u201d (Rev. 21:8).\nSlide 25: Our Future: Heaven will be magnificent. (22:18)\n\u201cAnd he carried me away in the Spirit to a mountain great and high, and showed me the\nHoly City, Jerusalem, coming down out of heaven from God. It shone with the glory of\nGod, and its brilliance was like that of a very precious jewel, like a jasper, clear as\ncrystal\u201d (Rev. 21:10-11).\nSlide 26: Our Future: The City will have Physical Boundaries. (23:30)\n\u201cIt had a great, high wall with twelve gates, and with twelve angels at the gates. On the\ngates were written the names of the twelve tribes of Israel\u201d (Rev. 21:12).\nSlide 27: Our Future: There are no Churches. (24:45)\n\u201cI did not see a temple in the city, because the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb are its\ntemple\u201d (Rev. 21:22)\n70\nSlide 28: Our Future: No Need for the Sun or Moon. (25:04)\n\u201cThe city does not need the sun or the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it\nlight, and the Lamb is its lamp\u201d (Rev. 21:23).\nSlide 29: Our Future: The Nations will be There. (25:13)\n\u201cThe nations will walk by its light, and the kings of the earth will bring their splendor into\nit. On no day will its gates ever be shut, for there will be no night there. The glory and\nhonor of the nations will be brought into it\u201d (Rev. 21:24-26).\nSlide 30: Our Future: It will be a Place of Perfect Peace (26:33)\n\u201cNothing impure will ever enter it, nor will anyone who does what is shameful or\ndeceitful, but only those whose names are written in the Lamb\u2019s book of life\u201d (Rev.\n21:27).\n71"